Dull bird in fennel in north/nw part of park. Still not certain on species but here are my thoughts based on the distinguishing characteristics listed by Kaufman in Field Guide to Advanced Birding. Crown: Brown with streaking and weak median stripe seems inconclusive for either Brewer's or Clay-colored but probably leaning Brewer's. Supercilium: Grayish, supporting Brewer's, but obviously distinct from crown and eye line, supporting Clay-colored. Doesn't appear to be invaded by streaking but edges don't appear to be very neat, so probably more leaning Brewer's. Malar: Dark lateral throat stripe with white submoustachial stripe point towards Clay-colored, maybe the strongest feature leaning in that direction. Neck and nape: Appears clean gray and contrasting with back crown color, supporting Clay-colored. However, in photos by other birders it looks like there is streaking on the back of the nape which points to Brewer's. Breast color: Appears grayish with no buffy tones, supporting Brewer's. Ear coverts: Strongly bordered not ruling out either species.  I think there was just one bird, but there might have been two. I encountered the bird(s) three times. Description in images indicate which encounter they are from.

Continuing along Alameda Creek trail, found by Derek and Jim yesterday. Small sparrow with clean gray nape and plain breast.  Update from 9/18: After hearing from others and examining my photos more closely, I'm changing this id to Brewer's Sparrow. The bird's markings are very dull, it lacks a pale median crown stripe, its supercilium is grayish with some streaking, and lateral throat stripe is weak.  It looks like this is a different bird than the one Derek photographed, and was apparently in a different part of the trail. But Derek and Jim saw at least two Spizella sparrows, so it's possible that they saw this bird as well.

Shortly before 1pm one other birder and I saw flashes of an orange face and white stripes down the back. At around 1pm there was a brief but intense downpour which drove away two of the three other birders present. After the rain stopped, the Nelson's Sparrow popped up for nice views of the orange face, gray nape, and white stripes along its back. I'm hoping that the other birder present at this time will post better photos; I only got this single terrible one which shows the orange supercilium, malar, and breast and gray median crown stripe. The bird went down and afterwards we only saw movement as it occasionally darted from one shrub to another.

Initially seen near the southeast entrance to the meadow, around 37.866724, -122.306349. Flushed when a jogger came by and not found again for a couple of hours, this time near information sign by the big willow patch around 37.867571, -122.306448. It then flew west but reemerged along the other path from the SE entrance, around 37.866834, -122.306984. It then stayed in the same general area, mostly sticking to the fences and weeds immediately next to them.  Very small, bright warbler. Blue grayish on top, white with a warm wash below. Noticeable light fuzzy eye ring. No wing bars. Rusty rump was difficult to see in the field but comes through in photos. The bird didn't seem very skulky. Often by itself but occasionally found with sparrows or Bushtits. Seemed to associate closely with Field Wormweed which can be seen in all of my photos.

Initially seen in the redwood tree at the end of the street, it then flew into the flowering tree in front of 661 Chetwood where it appeared to be drinking nectar. First seen at 9:05 and watched for about 15 minutes. Looks like it's missing a feather or two on its right breast.
Continuing in its favorite oak tree just down trail from the switchback with the rope swing. I watched it for about half an hour there starting at 4:30.

photos.Locality: Hayward Regional Shoreline--Winton Ave. access and parking area
photos.Observation Details: Along road to Winton Ave parking lot. Moving around a lot, both sides of the road, and calling some. Same area as recent Blackburnian warbler. Mostly yellow with reddish around base of tail and maybe some on face. Slight crest, no wing bars, big old bill.
Continuing male in its favorite tree, the second oak below the third switchback.

Seen twice, once around 9:20 in oaks just below the third switchback (the one with a rope swing) and once around 12:30 high in eucalyptus trees between the first and second switchback. Was silent during my first viewing but called a few times during my second.

Continuing bird seen briefly at 9:30 in eucalyptus tree above trail head where first seen two days ago. Around 10:10 I refound it higher up the trail in the oaks between the second and third switchbacks. From there it flew into the eucalyptus at the third switchback where the Acorn Woodpeckers live, then quickly flew into the canyon above the track and soccer field where I was unable to relocate it, though I did hear it call a couple of times. Bright, all red passerine with beady black eyes.

High up in the eucs between the first and second switchback, in the same general area one wintered last year. Bright red male.

photos.Media notes: The tanager appears to live up to the species' reputation by having a taste for bees.
photos.Observation Details: Seen twice, once around 9:20 in oaks just below the third switchback (the one with a rope swing) and once around 12:30 high in eucalyptus trees between the first and second switchback. Was silent during my first viewing but called a few times during my second.

Seen in the same area (riparian near dog park) with several other birders. Once it popped up at the top of some oaks, once flying between some tall pines, once eating pyracanthas berries below the canopy. Greenish tanager with dark wings lacking wing bars.

photos.Locality: Golden Gate Park--McLaren Lodge/Horseshoe Pits/Northeast Entrance
photos.Observation Details: Continuing yellow bird with thick bill and dark wings with wing bars.

Seen along Round Top Loop Trail north of EBMUD water structure as described by Elliot Chasin yesterday. Actively singing and perched prominently, giving great views. Unmistakable bird with black head and back, white belly, vibrant pink throat, and pale pink bill.

Continuing. Pink breast and underwings, black and white striped head and wings, streaks on breast and flanks. Mostly deep in the willow tree but came to the feeder briefly.
Continuing male. Solid rich blue with large bill and rufous wingbars. Perched prominently in an oak or nearby bay and singing his heart out the whole time I was in the area.
Seen in the same location as my last visit, around 37.874693, -122.224094. Calling but not singing.
Glad to see that at least one pair appears to be breeding here this year.

photos.Media notes: Female initiating copulation? A male flew beside her shortly after this photo was taken but they flew out of sight without mating.

photos.Observation Details: Continuing along the trail to the herb grench overlook, where it seemed to prefer the top of the only sizable conifer as a singing perch. Darker blue than lazuli and lacked wingbars and orange breast.

photos.Locality: Briones Regional Park--Bear Creek Staging Area
photos.Observation Details: Continuing completely rich blue songbird with dark lores and a gray beak in thistle field west of Abrigo Valley Trail at Maud Whalen camp. Took a bit of patience, but the bird eventually came up to a prominent perch and sang for about five minutes, giving great views.

Continuing in sw tule area. Very green above, yellow below, stout pink bill. My 400th California bird for the year!
